  <billdetail>
    <title>Electricity Industry Bill</title>
    <billtype>Government Bill</billtype>
    <repnote>As reported from the Finance and Expenditure Committee</repnote>
    <commentary id="DLM3019700" in.amend="false" irdnumbering="no" official="yes" bill.no="111" bill.type="government" stage="2" year="2009">
      <heading>Commentary</heading>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Recommendation</heading>
        <para>
          <text>The Finance and Expenditure Committee has examined the Electricity Industry Bill and recommends that it be passed with the amendments shown.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Introduction</heading>
        <para>
          <text>The Electricity Industry Bill seeks to reform various areas of the electricity sector, and is intended to increase competition in the electricity market and ensure security of supply. The bill would modify governance arrangements in the industry, provide for specific regulatory changes, and alter the overall structure of the electricity sector. Specifically, the bill would disestablish the Electricity Commission and replace it with an Electricity Authority, allow lines businesses back into retailing, incorporate the provisions of the Electricity (Continuance of Supply) Amendment Bill (as reported by the Commerce Committee in 2009), and reconfigure some assets of the three State-owned generators (Meridian Energy Limited, Mighty River Power Limited, and Genesis Power Limited).</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>This commentary concentrates on the more significant amendments we recommend to the legislation by majority, and discusses the major policy changes to the electricity industry that would be effected by the bill. It does not discuss the various minor clarification amendments or drafting corrections that we propose.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>State-owned enterprise asset transfers</heading>
        <para>
          <text>We were asked by the Minister of Energy and Resources to consider supplementary order paper No 121 alongside the bill. The SOP sets out in detail asset transfer arrangements for the Tekapo A and B power stations, and is intended to minimise costs, risks, and delays in relation to the transfer of consents to Genesis, and to ensure that current effects on the environment and rights and obligations regarding the stations are maintained throughout the transfer. Specifically, it provides for processes to deal with Waitaki Power Scheme consents in situations where consents may not be able to be simply transferred from Meridian to Genesis. It would also protect the rights and obligations of third parties that have agreements with Meridian regarding the Tekapo A and B stations. We recommend the inclusion in the bill of the provisions set out in the SOP, with some amendments, as discussed below.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend the insertion of new clause 124A into the bill, which sets out the purpose of the asset reconfiguration provisions. We propose an amendment to this clause as it was set out in the SOP, to ensure that it refers to effects on the environment as specified in the consent conditions of the Waitaki Power Scheme. The phrase <quote.in>maintain current effects on the environment</quote.in> might be interpreted too broadly. As environmental effects may vary over time, we consider the clause should be narrowed to cover only those effects that result from the consent conditions. We also propose that the clause make it clearer that the purpose of the provisions includes the maintenance of rights and obligations of permits and agreements with third parties.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>The SOP as originally drafted included a provision which (if adopted) would have provided powers for shareholding Ministers to give directions on contracts between Meridian and Genesis, such as a water management agreement. However, the drafting of the provision in the SOP would only have allowed a water management agreement to maintain environmental effects, which we consider is too narrow. We therefore recommend changes to the bill to allow wider powers for shareholding Ministers to give directions under clause 124(2)(d) that include any contracts necessary or desirable to achieve the purposes of new clause 124(1).</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>For clarification purposes, we also recommend that new clause 124G make it clear that nothing in the bill affects the Waitaki Catchment Water Allocation Plan, or affects the application of the Plan to consents amended or transferred as part of the asset transfer process. Although it would not be appropriate for implementation of the Plan to be accelerated under the asset transfer provisions of the bill, we consider that some clarification that its application to amended or transferred consents would be unchanged is necessary to avoid confusion.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We also recommend the insertion of new clause 124C, to allow the Minister of Energy and Resources, in consultation with the Minister for the Environment, to change the permit conditions by order if it proves impracticable for generators to meet some Waitaki Power Scheme consent conditions. In the bill as introduced, there are no provisions to resolve such a situation. We consider that these amendments would provide for a timely and effective resolution in this situation.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We also recommend the insertion of new clauses 124D to 124F, which concern existing arrangements with Meridian relating to the Waitaki Power Scheme and the Tekapo stations. The new clauses provide for shareholding Ministers to direct Meridian and Genesis to negotiate the retention, transfer, sharing, or splitting of these agreements between themselves, then offer to third parties before a specified date any replacement agreements necessary to maintain the rights and obligations of the existing agreements. However, in the event that this process does not lead to a satisfactory outcome, these new provisions would also allow the shareholding Ministers to direct the generators on which agreements are to remain with Meridian, which are to be transferred to Genesis, and which are to be shared by Genesis. The provisions would also enable parties to the existing agreements other than Meridian or Genesis to terminate their agreements by notice to the Minister, Meridian, and Genesis. The bill as introduced does not provide for resolutions in such circumstances.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>These amendments would provide appropriate powers to deal with these situations if they should arise. In new clause 124E we propose that Genesis and Meridian be permitted to offer more than one replacement contract to third parties, recognising that in some cases there will be two contracts, one from Meridian and one from Genesis. We also consider that subclauses (6) and (7) should refer to rights, liabilities, entitlements, and obligations; obligations are not included in the SOP as introduced. Finally, we consider these two subclauses should apply from the date specified in a direction, rather than the date on which the transfer takes place (as proposed in the SOP). This would better clarify their intent.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We also recommend, in new clause 124G(2), a provision that there is no right to appeal decisions or directions made under new clauses 124B to 124F. We consider limiting rights of appeal to be justified by the need to prevent delays, given that the objective of the new subpart is to maintain current effects on the environment and rights and obligations. We are advised that third parties would still have the right to terminate an agreement, and could also challenge the Minister’s interpretation of law through a judicial review.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend that new clause 124D provide that, in addition to the agreements already in new schedule 4A, any other written agreements that the Minister considered directly related to the ownership and operation of Tekapo A and B power stations, and which Meridian would no longer require or be able to honour as a result of the transfer, are subject to the provisions in new clause 124E. This would ensure that rights and obligations in other agreements not specifically provided for in the schedule would be maintained. We have not included all the agreements proposed in the SOP, as some have been replaced by subsequent agreements.</text>
        </para>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Other amendments</heading>
          <para>
            <text>We recommend replacing the provisions in clause 124(7) as introduced in order to extend the protections for directors to the State generator as well as its employees, contractors, and advisers (new clause 124AB). The bill as introduced provides directors of a State generator with protections only in relation to following a direction from shareholding Ministers, and we consider it appropriate to extend these protections to the company itself and to others who might otherwise be liable under a number of Acts for the consequences of following a Ministerial direction. We also recommend that the protections for directors, employees, contractors, and advisers (but not the company itself) be extended to cover breaches of non-statutory duties, to remove the potential for personal liability to third parties for complying with a Ministerial direction.</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Further, we also recommend inserting new clause 128 to provide that actions or omissions by a State generator pursuant to a Ministerial direction would be authorised under section 43 of the Commerce Act 1986. This amendment would ensure protection from action should breaches or liabilities arise from directions regarding transfers and contracts, including water management agreements. In addition, new subclause 2 would ensure that section 47 of the Commerce Act concerning business acquisitions would not apply to the transfer of assets. While the risk of breaches of the Commerce Act would be low because transfers and contracts have a pro-competitive purpose, this amendment would remove the need for State generators to seek authorisations and clearances, which would be time-consuming and resource-intensive. </text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Asset transfer issues</heading>
          <para>
            <text>We are aware of some concern about the benefits and risks of transferring the Tekapo A and B power stations from Meridian Energy to Genesis Energy. For example, some submitters were concerned that the transfer would reduce efficiency (by increasing water spill), security of supply, the standard of flood management, and the reliability of irrigation, and disrupt established relationships and agreements, for little gain in retail competition. There was also concern that a detailed cost-benefit analysis of the transfer had not been undertaken.</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Conversely, some submitters were in favour of the asset transfer, arguing that it would improve competition in the retail market, especially in the South Island, and help improve the competitive situation in the wholesale market, particularly with regard to water management.</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>We consider that the benefits of the transfer outweigh the risks, and are satisfied that sufficient cost-benefit analysis has been completed. We believe that the transfer would create more retail competition in the South Island; this effect has been demonstrated to some extent already, with Genesis advertising competitive prices in the Christchurch, Dunedin, and Queenstown markets in anticipation of the transfer. This competition implies more scope for interest in building new generation in the South Island. We also consider that the transfer is likely to introduce more diversity into the risk management of stored water.</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>While we acknowledge that there is a risk of the asset transfer reducing the efficiency of water management, we have been assured that this risk would be relatively small, as Genesis would have strong commercial incentives to operate the Tekapo stations in a similar way to Meridian. In addition, we are advised that the water agreement between Meridian and Genesis is expected to include provision for management of extreme events, including flooding, very dry years, and excessive inflows. Furthermore, we are advised that there is very little risk that the transfer will reduce security of supply; in fact, an increase, if anything, is more likely to result from higher average lake levels and more diverse views on the value of water at any given time.</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>We also consider that the provisions in the bill requiring the State generators to enter into long-term financial contracts with each other (<quote.in>virtual asset swaps</quote.in>) would encourage retail competition by Mighty River Power and Genesis in the South Island and Meridian in the North Island. In addition, we consider that the proposed transfer of the Whirinaki power station would help to provide Meridian with capacity to back up its hydro generation, and partly compensate it for the loss of its Tekapo stations. Implementation costs of virtual asset swaps are expected to be minimal, estimated at $1–2 million. As the bill does not include the specific details of the virtual asset swaps, which are subject to discussion between the relevant entities and the Government, it is not appropriate for us to comment further on this matter. Some of us have concerns about asset transfer issues, which we have discussed in our minority view.</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>We note that a reasonable phase-in period for the transfers is likely, which should minimise any resultant disruption. We encourage the Government to consider a long transitional period for the virtual asset swaps and the Whirinaki transfer, to allow time for any problems created by the transfer to be dealt with adequately.</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Therefore, we recommend inserting new clause 125 to make it clear that the reserve energy scheme should continue until (but not after) the sale of Whirinaki to Meridian is complete, unless an earlier date is set by the Minister. This would ensure that Whirinaki could remain available, for example over winter 2011 if necessary, for security of supply purposes.</text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Ownership and corporate separation thresholds for lines companies</heading>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend some amendments to Part 3 of the bill governing the rules for lines businesses undertaking generating and retailing, in order to increase ownership and separation thresholds. Under the bill as introduced, lines companies could undertake retailing on their networks without quantity caps, and build any type of generation. Certain restrictions would be placed on these activities, however, including a threshold of 100 MW at which ownership separation would be required between distribution (lines) businesses and generation; and a threshold of 5 GW/year for retail and 10 MW for generation for corporate separation and arm’s-length rules. These thresholds are intended to prevent large-scale vertical integration of generator-retailers and lines businesses, and to reduce the risk of anti-competitive practices.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>However, we consider that these thresholds are set too low in the bill as introduced, and might have the unintended effect of discouraging lines companies from entering generation or retailing, or from investing in sufficient generation to manage plant risks and the risks of entering the retail market effectively. Therefore, we recommend that the threshold for ownership separation be raised from 100 to 250 MW for generation connected to the grid, and the threshold for corporate separation be raised from 5 to 75 GW/year for retail and from 10 to 50 MW for generation (clause 74). These amendments would provide appropriate incentives for lines companies to enter retail and generation markets, while still preventing anti-competitive practices and large-scale vertical integration of lines with existing integrated generation-retailing companies.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We consider that these provisions should also make it clear that the ownership restrictions would apply only to generation connected directly to the national grid, and that there would be no restriction on the quantity of generation a lines company might own connected to local networks.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Further, we recommend amendments to clause 7 of schedule 3 to raise the requirement for one independent director to two, because of the substantial increase in the threshold for corporate separation. This would be more in line with guidance on independent directors from the Securities Commission and the New Zealand and Australian stock exchanges. We consider this amendment necessary as we believe thresholds related to the size of a network would be more complex to administer, and cannot clearly be justified as compliance costs would be the same in all cases.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Some of us have concerns regarding changing thresholds, and have discussed this in our minority view.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Line tariff standardisation</heading>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend inserting new clauses 45(2)(e) and (ea). Clause 45 provides for the Minister to amend the Electricity Industry Participation Code to require more standardisation of line tariff structures and use-of-system agreements by lines companies. We are assured that the relevant provisions of the Code in relation to this issue would not prevent tariffs for demand management. We recommend that lines companies that directly bill their customers be exempt from the “more standardised tariff structure” requirement, because the complexity of line tariffs which are billed directly does not affect retail competition. We also recommend that new clause 45(2)(ea) require use-of-system agreements to include indemnities for retailers for liabilities under the Consumer Guarantees Act 1993 for breaches of acceptable quality caused by faults in the network over which the retailer has no control, because the lines business is a monopoly provider. We consider this amendment necessary to ensure that retailers are not held responsible for issues they cannot control or influence.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading><quote.in>Smart</quote.in> electricity meters</heading>
        <para>
          <text>We considered including in the bill a provision to establish mandatory standards for smart meters; however, the majority of us do not believe such a provision is necessary at this stage. We are advised that the Electricity Commission considered this issue carefully in 2009, and concluded that regulation for home area network capability was not yet necessary in New Zealand for the following reasons: the technology for smart meters is not fully developed yet, so there is a risk that mandated standards might become obsolete; there is a high level of compliance with existing voluntary guidelines; and regulating the rollout of smart meters now may incur further costs for consumers without providing many benefits. The commission also noted that the case for regulation in New Zealand is less strong than elsewhere, because ripple control of hot water can be used to manage peak load, and because the commission considers the rollout of smart meters to be progressing at a reasonable speed.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We were assured that the Electricity Authority would monitor the development of smart meters closely, and that its powers under the Electricity Industry Participation Code allow it to set mandatory standards at any time. In addition, we are advised that the Minister of Energy and Resources can request the Authority to review any matter, including smart metering, under clause 20 of the bill.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Electricity Authority</heading>
        <para>
          <text>To improve clarity and consistency, we propose amending the clauses governing the Authority’s powers relating to monitoring, investigation, and enforcement, by deleting clause 21 and clauses 50 to 53, and redrafting them as new clauses 47A to 47D to restrict the Authority’s powers where they relate to monitoring. We consider that the power to require information and other documents should be available only against industry participants (and not against <quote.in>any person</quote.in>), and the Authority should not be able to require access to premises for monitoring purposes, even under a warrant.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We also recommend changes to the provisions relating to privileges (contained in proposed new clause 47D). We propose that it be clearly stated that the prohibition on refusing to answer questions or provide documents applies to industry participants as well as their officers or employees. In the bill as introduced, this is unclear. However, we believe that the restriction on the use of self-incriminating statements and documents should apply only to officers and employees, because otherwise the value of the Authority’s power to require information and documents would be lost.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We also recommend amendments to clauses 12 and 13 to clarify the criteria for making, varying, and revoking individual exemptions from requirements to register as an industry participant and to comply with the Electricity Industry Participation Code. We consider that the Authority should be able to grant individual exemptions only if it is satisfied that it is not necessary for an industry participant to be registered and to comply in order to achieve its objectives under clause 17, and the exemption is desirable to reduce overall administration and compliance costs. We believe that the Authority should be permitted to vary or revoke an individual exemption if it is satisfied that it is necessary or desirable to do so to achieve the objectives under clause 17, and that this should outweigh any increase in administrative and compliance costs. In addition, we consider that the Authority should be required to give notice to exempted parties (where they are identifiable) of its intention to vary or revoke an individual exemption, and give them a reasonable opportunity to comment. These amendments should give more certainty to industry participants on the criteria and processes the Authority would use when considering exemptions and amendments to exemptions.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Rulings Panel </heading>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend a number of small amendments to some of the provisions governing Rulings Panel processes.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend an amendment to clause 56(1)(d) to make the maximum pecuniary penalty the Rulings Panel could impose $200,000. The bill as introduced sets the maximum at $2 million. We are concerned that a penalty as large as $2 million could, for instance, discourage industry participants from providing particular services or encourage unnecessary risk aversion. Amending the maximum to $200,000 would make a substantial penalty available, while still minimising possible disincentives to industry participants. We also recommend that clause 58 be amended to require the application of the listed criteria to the decision on whether to make a pecuniary penalty, and to determining the amount of any penalty. At present, the criteria set out in the bill apply only to the decision on the amount of the penalty, and not on whether or not to impose it.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We also recommend amendments to clause 66 of the bill to widen the range of rulings that can be appealed against. Under the bill as introduced, only suspension or termination orders and the amount of pecuniary and compensation orders could be appealed; we propose that this be widened to include orders for a public warning or reprimand and compliance orders. We consider this consistent with the principle of allowing appeals on decisions wherever possible. However, we do not believe that allowing appeals against other panel decisions, such as private reprimands or recommendations for rule changes, is warranted, because appeals against these decisions would be unnecessary or problematic. For instance, rule changes proposed by the panel would be subject to a thorough process under clauses 41 and 42 of the bill, so it would not be appropriate for them to be reviewed first by the courts.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We also recommend that clause 27 be amended to specify that the Minister of Energy and Resources would have the lead role in appointing members to the Rulings Panel, in consultation with the Minister of Justice. In the bill as introduced, the two ministers would be jointly responsible; we consider that it would be better to have one minister take the lead because it would be administratively complicated to have ministers acting jointly.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We also recommend the insertion of new clause 55(1) to provide that a hearing of the panel would have to comprise the chairperson (or deputy chairperson if the chairperson was not available) and two other members appointed by the chairperson (or deputy chairperson) from the panel. In the bill as introduced, a hearing of the Rulings Panel could require five members, which we consider to be excessive. We also propose an amendment to clause 27 to clarify that the Governor-General should appoint the chairperson and deputy chairperson.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend amending clause 29 to specify that the remuneration of the Rulings Panel would be set by the Remuneration Authority, rather than by the Cabinet fees framework. This would bring the panel into line with the remuneration determination for the Authority’s board. However, expenses of the panel should be set in accordance with the Cabinet fees framework.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Enforcement of the Electricity Industry Participation Code</heading>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend an amendment to clause 57 to protect all market operation service providers, not just the system operator, from tort action. This amendment is consistent with current legislation, and would avoid higher costs for liability insurance (where it was available) and unnecessarily discouraging competition for service provider contracts.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We also recommend amendments to clause 119, which provides for regulations to be made on monitoring, investigating, and enforcing the Code. We consider that the Minister should not need to consult with the Authority on the initial set of regulations, provided that the regulations carry over the provisions of the Electricity Governance Regulations 2003 and that the Minister or the Electricity Commission has consulted interested parties on any material amendments. We therefore recommend the insertion of subclause (1A) to provide an exemption from the consultation requirements in these circumstances. Exempting the initial set of regulations from consultation would also mean that the initial set of regulations could come into effect on 1 October, the same day as the Authority would be established, as the Minister would not need to wait to consult with the Authority. We also recommend amending the regulation-making power in this clause to include the ability to create offences, to ensure the regulations can be enforced. We recommend that this clause make it clear that it would be an offence, punishable by a fine not exceeding $20,000, to fail to comply with a requirement of the regulations (clause 119(1)(h).</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Consumer issues</heading>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend some amendments to the provisions allowing price restraint for line charges for domestic and rural consumers (contained in subpart 4 of Part 4, clauses 111 to 115, of the bill). Specifically, we recommend that these provisions be narrowed to apply only to the rate of change of rural line charges relative to the rate of change of comparable non-rural line charges in the same network. We also recommend moving these provisions to clause 120, which provides for regulation-making powers relating to tariffs and other consumer issues, and that new clause 120(2)(g) stipulate that fines for breaching regulations may be prescribed in the regulations up to a maximum of $100,000, rather than $500,000.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We believe that these provisions should be narrowed because, although the ability to regulate domestic line charges is now redundant as a result of the price control provisions in Part 4 of the Commerce Act 1986, some powers are still needed to reinforce the policy intention of avoiding disparities between rural and non-rural line charges.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We also recommend amendments to clause 98, which relates to exemptions from the obligation to be a member of the dispute resolution scheme, to resemble the exemption provisions in clauses 12 and 13, and to reflect our proposed amendments to those provisions. We believe that the criteria and processes for exemptions and their variance and revocation should be spelt out in the bill, to make their intention clear and avoid any confusion about the process. We also recommend amending clause 98 to insert a notification provision for exemptions. The bill as introduced includes no requirement to publicise exemptions under this clause, even though the clause relates to a dispute resolution scheme that would allow complaints to be made by consumers. This amendment would bring this provision into line with clauses 12 and 13, which would require the Electricity Authority to publicise a list of exemptions from registration and compliance with the Code respectively.</text>
        </para>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Supply to remote consumers</heading>
          <para>
            <text>We recommend amending clause 110 to make it clear that the Commerce Commission must count the costs of alternative supply to remote consumers under clause 107(2) or the costs of an agreement to end the obligation to supply under clause 108(1) as a cost for the supply of line function services, where those costs were lower than the cost of supplying line function services. This amendment is intended to remove a disincentive, pointed out in submissions, for distributors to offer and consumers to accept less costly alternative means of meeting their energy requirements.</text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Electricity prices</heading>
          <para>
            <text>We are aware of concern that electricity prices have risen substantially faster for retail customers than for commercial and industrial users in the past 10 or so years, and some submitters expressed their view that retail consumers may be effectively cross-subsidising these other groups. Although we are advised that no cross-subsidisation is likely to be taking place in a technical sense, we believe it is clear that residential consumers are paying higher retail margins than other consumer groups. We are informed that this is probably because of weak competition in the retail market for residential consumers, particularly in the South Island. While the bill promotes measures intended to improve competition, and thus help to constrain electricity prices or price increases, we are advised that upward pressure on prices will continue because of the cost of building new power stations and upgrading transmission infrastructure to meet demand, and the cost of gas to fuel power stations. The majority of us believe that the pro-competitive measures in the bill will go some way to combat substantial price rises, and look forward to seeing progress. However, some of us remain concerned that these measures alone will not reduce power prices, or stop large price increases, and consider that further initiatives are needed to effect such an outcome.</text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Amendments to the Commerce Act 1986</heading>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend some further amendments to the Commerce Act, many of which are for clarification or to address drafting matters (subpart 4 of Part 5).</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend an amendment to clause 145(3) to allow the remaining trustees of consumer trusts to appoint one trustee until the next election in the event of a casual vacancy. This should avoid the cost of unnecessary by-elections.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We also recommend an amendment to section 54V(4) of the Act (in clause 149) to allow more flexibility to the way the Commerce Commission applies quality standards set by the Electricity Authority when undertaking price-quality regulation of Transpower. The additional flexibility would allow the Commerce Commission to develop effective incentives for Transpower to meet or exceed quality standards. We also recommend that clause 47 be amended to insert a new provision for Transpower to recover its revenue from designated transmission customers, using the transmission pricing methodology in the Electricity Industry Participation Code. We consider it desirable to avoid disputes over the recovery of approved expenditure by Transpower.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend the insertion of a transitional provision (new clause 139A) to allow for the costs of the Commerce Commission in preparing to take on its new functions relating to grid upgrade proposals to be recovered by levies. The levies are currently payable under section 53ZE of the Commerce Act. The Commerce Commission began incurring these costs from 1 January 2010, but the levies would normally apply only to costs incurred after this bill came into force. We consider that this provision is justified as it would ensure that the commission would be ready to take up its new functions as soon as the bill was enacted.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We also recommend the insertion of new clause 142A, which is a substitution for clause 150. Clause 150 would have allowed the making of regulations to authorise repayment by the Commission of excess application fees paid by those seeking a customised price-quality path. New clause 142A would amend section 53Y of the Act, which allows for the recovery of the Commission’s costs through those fees. New clause 142A would also clarify that the recoverable costs are those involved in assessing and reconsidering proposals, and not just in setting customised price-quality paths.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Finally, we recommend two minor amendments to clause 149 to make it clear that the Electricity Authority would be required to consult the Commerce Commission before implementing any changes to the Code which were likely to be relevant to the powers, duties, and functions of the Commission under the Commerce Act; and also that the Authority must advise the Commission on any new costs imposed on lines businesses or Transpower because of new Code or regulatory requirements.</text>
        </para>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Liquid hedge market</heading>
          <para>
            <text>We recommend that anything done or omitted by industry participants to develop and operate a liquid hedge market be authorised under section 43 of the Commerce Act (clause 128). We consider that a liquid hedge market is essential for facilitating competition in the electricity market, and specifically for encouraging entry by new generators and retailers such as lines businesses. This amendment would avoid the need for industry participants to obtain authorisations from the Commerce Commission, which could be time-consuming and costly.</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>We are advised that the risks of industry participants developing anti-competitive practices under this amendment are minimal. The Minister of Energy and Resources has set out strict requirements for an acceptable hedge market, in an effort to minimise barriers to entry and liquidity. If these requirements are not complied with, or anti-competitive practices develop, the Electricity Authority, and subsequently the Minister under clause 46, would have the power to set mandatory requirements under the Code.</text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Other minor amendments</heading>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend deleting clause 7, which contains the definition of <quote.in>the electricity industry</quote.in>. We considered amending this definition, which is unsatisfactory in excluding major electricity consumers and demand-side participants. However, we were advised that finding a precise definition would be difficult, and as the clause was for explanatory purposes and had no legal effect, the most appropriate action would be to delete it. We are assured that it will be sufficient to rely on the generally accepted meaning of <quote.in>electricity industry</quote.in>. </text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We also recommend an amendment to clause 46(3) to clarify that the Minister would be required to consult all interested parties before amending the Code. In the bill as introduced, the Minister would have to consult only the Authority; we consider that all interested parties should be consulted on changes that may affect them. </text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We also recommend amending clause 90 to simplify the provisions relating to the disclosure of information to the Authority. The bill as introduced would require all distributors selling electricity to connected customers to send an independently audited certificate to the Authority. As this would be unduly onerous, especially if the threshold for corporate separation is raised as we recommend, we consider that the requirement should be that distributors selling more than 5 GWh/year on a local network must, within two months of the end of a financial year, disclose annually to the Commerce Commission the quantity of electricity sold by a connected retailer or retailers to customers connected to its local network.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We also recommend amending clause 120 to require the Minister to obtain and consider advice from the Authority on the impact of proposed regulations on efficiency, competition, and reliability. We consider this amendment appropriate to ensure that the Minister would be fully aware of the consequences of regulating on issues affecting consumers. We also recommend amending this clause to enable regulations to be made regarding the power to regulate charges for supply by alternative means to remote rural consumers under clause 107(2)(b). This amendment would ensure rates were fair for rural remote consumers.<footnote id="DLM3019701"><para><text> This amendment formed part of the Commerce Committee’s recommendations on the Electricity (Continuance of Supply) Amendment Bill, and was overlooked in error in the bill as introduced. </text></para></footnote> </text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Finally, we recommend amending the definition of <quote.in>electrical installation</quote.in> in the Electricity Act 1992. We recommend the definition specify that an electrical installation does not include a generator within a property where that generator is capable of supplying electricity to the supply system independent of the supply of electricity to an installation on that property.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>New Zealand Labour Party minority view</heading>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Bill fails to balance essential priorities</heading>
          <para>
            <text>Labour opposes the Electricity Industry Bill because it fails to balance the priorities of security of supply and transmission, affordability and predictability of pricing, and the sustainable production and use of electricity. The bill fails to meet the Government’s own stated goals and objectives for the sector, and is in fact likely to exacerbate many of the problems which the sector currently faces.</text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Bill removes equity and environmental protections and imposes incoherent policy solutions</heading>
          <para>
            <text>The bill, if passed, will mean that it is no longer possible to regard electricity as anything akin to a public good in New Zealand.  Instead, it becomes an entirely tradable commodity. By way of example, under existing legislation, the Electricity Commission, created by Labour to provide better coordination within the sector, has statutory objectives that include ensuring fairness and sustainability in the supply of electricity. These objectives are removed from the functions of the Electricity Authority, one of the bureaucracies proposed to replace the Commission. Domestic consumers and advocates of sustainable energy will thus be left with no option but to advance their interests by lobbying Ministers directly. As in other energy policy-related areas, such as the amendments last year to the Emissions Trading Scheme, this is not coherent regulation based on well-analysed policy. Instead, it perpetuates the present Government’s practice of promoting ad hoc policies.</text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Bill implements proposals that have not been properly evaluated</heading>
          <para>
            <text>Significant measures advanced by the bill, notably its central proposal to take generation assets from one State-Owned Enterprise and bestow them on another, have not been subject to rigorous analysis. Nor have the risks arising from some of these proposals been properly evaluated. This view is shared by number of submitters, with significant experience of the sector and whose views are entitled to weight, who told us that the level of analysis for the costs, benefits, and risks associated with some proposals was insufficient.</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>This view is reinforced by the Treasury’s Regulatory Impact Analysis Team, who considered the regulatory impact assessment for the bill was lacking in certain areas and should:</text>
            <list>
              <item>
                <label auto.number="no" denominator="no">•</label>
                <para>
                  <text><quote.in>. . . have included a more comprehensive discussion of the risks associated with proposed options</quote.in>;</text>
                </para>
              </item>
              <item>
                <label auto.number="no" denominator="no">•</label>
                <para>
                  <text><quote.in>. . . provide a better idea of the magnitude of costs and benefits of the options discussed in comparison to the problem they are trying to address</quote.in>;</text>
                </para>
              </item>
              <item>
                <label auto.number="no" denominator="no">•</label>
                <para>
                  <text>have <quote.in>. . . better reflected the range of views received during consultation</quote.in>; and</text>
                </para>
              </item>
              <item>
                <label auto.number="no" denominator="no">•</label>
                <para>
                  <text>have contained <quote.in>. . . a discussion of whether or not the options proposed have been tried overseas and, if so, what their impact was</quote.in>.</text>
                </para>
              </item>
            </list>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Bill will not control price increases</heading>
          <para>
            <text>The Government has stated that the central purpose of the Electricity Industry bill is to improve competition in the electricity market, and to improve security of supply. But officials advised us that measures to increase security of supply generally put upward pressure on prices. Contact Energy Ltd confirmed in its evidence that it will need to continue to raise retail prices by up to 5 percent per annum if it is to continue to invest profitably in new generation capacity. We are not confident that the measures contained in the bill will lead to lower price rises in the sector.</text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Bill’s asset-swap proposal will increase supply risks</heading>
          <para>
            <text>Instead, it is likely that electricity prices will continue to rise to reflect increased supply risks. And the bill, if passed, will increase those risks. As Trustpower has said:</text>
            <quote indented="no">
              <para>
                <text>“the uncertainty created by the industry shake-up (is) likely to have a chilling effect on private electricity generators’ willingness to invest in new electricity plant, raising the prospect of shortages again within a decade”.<footnote id="DLM3019702"><para><text> National Business Review, 9 December 2009. </text></para></footnote></text>
              </para>
            </quote>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>The Ministerial Review in which the bill had its origins noted that New Zealand remains vulnerable to dry year shortages because of the predominance of hydro generation in New Zealand’s generation portfolio and the lack of options for hydro shortage. The provisions in this bill that will see the transfer of the Tekapo A and B generation assets from Meridian Energy to Genesis will do nothing to increase security of energy supply. Indeed, a number of reputable submitters were concerned that it will increase supply risks. The Institution of Professional Engineers New Zealand (IPENZ) raised concerns that the transfer will compromise the integrity of the Waitaki hydro system, leading to suboptimal outcomes resulting from the joint operation of the system by two generators leading to a reduction in security of supply. Compelling concerns were raised that the transfer will result in a loss of efficiency across the catchment from increased water spill from Lake Tekapo.</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>The transfer of physical assets contains a high degree of risk and few observable benefits. The Ministry of Economic Development advised us that</text>
            <quote indented="no">
              <para>
                <text>“it is not possible to prove that the benefits of the transfer will exceed costs and risks”.<footnote id="DLM3019703"><para><text> Officials’ report on submissions to the Finance and Expenditure Committee, 16 April 2010, <emphasis style="italic">Electricity Industry Bill</emphasis>, p. 7</text></para></footnote> </text>
              </para>
            </quote>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>The Treasury also expressed scepticism about any net benefits arising out of the asset swap proposal, and considers that there are significant risks arising out of the proposed transfers, including the potential for a loss of operational efficiency within the Waitaki catchment. The Treasury also pointed to issues with resource consents relating to water usage within the Waitaki catchment that could flow from the transfer proposal. We are not satisfied that these concerns have been addressed by suggested amendments to the bill.</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>A recent report from Standard and Poors also highlights a degree of risk from the asset transfer proposals. Standard and Poors note that one of their biggest concerns is </text>
            <quote indented="no">
              <para>
                <text>“. . . that without appropriate support to the balance sheets—the gentailers . . . do not have the financial headroom to withstand the risks of transitioning to the new environment”.<footnote id="DLM3019704"><para><text> Standard and Poors, 22 April 2010, press release, New Zealand Power Market Reforms Still Pose Major Credit Challenges for Generator-Retailers, Report says; Iyer, Parvathy, and Creed, Richard, 21 April 2010, <emphasis style="italic">Industry Report Card: Spotlight On New Zealand’s Power Generator-Retailers: Can Weak Balance Sheets Accommodate Market Reforms and Growth Ambitions?</emphasis></text></para></footnote></text>
              </para>
            </quote>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>On balance, the suggested benefits of increased retail competition in the South Island (even if they eventuate which, according to the evidence we heard, is dubious) simply do not justify the risks that arise out of the proposal to transfer generation assets between generators.</text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Bill may undesirably entrench monopoly positions</heading>
          <para>
            <text>Ironically, given the overall thrust of the bill to introduce more market solutions to the energy sector, a number of submitters pointed to provisions that run the risk of entrenching natural monopolies, and therefore price increases, in some areas.  Examples to which we were directed include:</text>
            <list>
              <item>
                <label auto.number="no" denominator="no">•</label>
                <para>
                  <text>The removal of the role of consumers and sustainable energy suppliers in the conversion of the present Electricity Market Rulebook to the new Code, risking more oligopolistic behaviour by generator retailers;</text>
                </para>
              </item>
              <item>
                <label auto.number="no" denominator="no">•</label>
                <para>
                  <text>The proposed standardisation of distribution price schemes, with a consequent risk that lines companies will lose opportunities to reduce costs specific to their own networks;</text>
                </para>
              </item>
              <item>
                <label auto.number="no" denominator="no">•</label>
                <para>
                  <text>Establishing Transpower as the system operator by statute.  Retaining contestability in that role encourages the system operator to perform efficiently, operate independently, and in the best interest of the market overall; and</text>
                </para>
              </item>
              <item>
                <label auto.number="no" denominator="no">•</label>
                <para>
                  <text>Allowing lines companies back into retailing, if that occurs in a way that will create barriers to entry, especially in small network areas.</text>
                </para>
              </item>
            </list>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Bill does nothing to bring coherence to energy policy framework</heading>
          <para>
            <text>We remain concerned that the Government proposes to proceed with the bill without reference to wider energy policy issues.  There is still no certainty over the status of the New Zealand Energy Strategy. The Minister of Energy said in February 2010 that he would update that Strategy. No further announcements on that update have been forthcoming. A long-term plan for a sustainable energy sector is a key element of the Strategy. It is folly to amend the legislative framework applicable to the electricity sector in the absence of any statement of the present Government’s long-term vision for the energy sector (if in fact such a vision exists). But it perhaps serves to explain the almost complete lack of regard for environmental and conservation matters—such as a failure to promote smart metering—in a bill regulating a sector in which these should be amongst the primary considerations.</text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Conclusion</heading>
          <para>
            <text>The Electricity Industry Bill fails to address the major issues facing the electricity sector. It will not deliver even on the priorities that the Government has set out for itself. It is likely to exacerbate pressures on security of supply and electricity affordability.</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>At the earliest opportunity, a future Labour-led Government will repeal it and replace it with a legislative framework that ensures that New Zealanders have a secure supply of electricity that is:</text>
            <list>
              <item>
                <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                <para>
                  <text>affordable;</text>
                </para>
              </item>
              <item>
                <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                <para>
                  <text>priced predictably; and</text>
                </para>
              </item>
              <item>
                <label auto.number="no" denominator="yes"/>
                <para>
                  <text>produced and used sustainably.</text>
                </para>
              </item>
            </list>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.appendix>
        <heading>Appendix</heading>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Committee process</heading>
          <para>
            <text>The Electricity Industry Bill was referred to us on 15 December 2009. The closing date for submissions was 26 February 2010. We received and considered 51 submissions from interested groups and individuals. We heard 33 submissions.</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>We called for further submissions on Supplementary Order Paper No 121. The closing date for submissions was Friday 14 May. We received and considered 16 submissions, and heard nine submissions.</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>We received advice from the Ministry of Economic Development.</text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Committee membership</heading>
          <para>
            <text>Craig Foss (Chairperson)</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Amy Adams</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>David Bennett</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Brendon Burns</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>John Boscawen</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Hon David Cunliffe</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Aaron Gilmore</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Raymond Huo</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Rahui Katene</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Peseta Sam Lotu-Iiga</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Stuart Nash</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Dr Russel Norman</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Charles Chauvel replaced Raymond Huo and Dr Kennedy Graham replaced Dr Russel Norman for this item of business.</text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
      </comm.appendix>
    </commentary>
